3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"dYdX calculates funding rates every hour using a time-weighted average price mechanism comparing the perpetual contract price to the underlying ORDI spot price. The platform's Cosmos appchain architecture enables more frequent funding settlements compared to traditional 8-hour cycles. Funding payments occur automatically between long and short position holders based on the rate direction, with positive rates requiring longs to pay shorts."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ORDI","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ORDI represents the largest market cap Bitcoin ordinal token, making it a key indicator for the broader ordinals ecosystem. The token's volatility and correlation with Bitcoin network activity create distinct funding rate patterns that differ from traditional altcoins. This creates arbitrage opportunities particularly during Bitcoin ordinals hype cycles or network congestion periods."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ORDI funding rates on dYdX have shown extreme volatility correlating with Bitcoin ordinal inscription activity and broader BRC-20 token sentiment. During the initial ordinals boom in early 2023, funding rates frequently exceeded 0.5% per hour as speculative demand drove perpetual prices above spot. The token exhibits strong correlation with Bitcoin network fees and transaction volumes, often seeing funding spikes during periods of high ordinal minting activity. Unlike traditional altcoins, ORDI funding patterns closely follow Bitcoin ecosystem developments rather than general crypto market trends."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"The relatively low liquidity of ORDI compared to major cryptocurrencies creates significant funding rate arbitrage potential on dYdX. Traders can exploit the 1-hour funding intervals by taking opposite positions on centralized exchanges with 8-hour funding cycles, capturing rate differentials during volatile periods. The decentralized nature of dYdX allows for more sophisticated arbitrage strategies without KYC constraints, particularly valuable for institutional arbitrageurs managing large portfolios. Cross-exchange arbitrage between dYdX and major CEXes like Binance or OKX can be profitable when funding rate spreads exceed transaction costs and slippage."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ORDI's small market cap and concentrated holder base create significant liquidation risks during extreme market movements, particularly when Bitcoin ordinal sentiment shifts rapidly. The token's dependence on Bitcoin network activity means funding rates can be unpredictable during network congestion or protocol changes affecting ordinal inscriptions. dYdX's post-migration lower liquidity compared to its StarkEx days means larger positions face increased slippage and potential difficulty in execution during volatile periods. Smart contract risks on the Cosmos appchain, while reduced compared to Ethereum-based DEXes, still present custody concerns for large arbitrage positions."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"What makes ORDI funding rates different on dYdX compared to other DEXes?","answer":"dYdX's 1-hour funding intervals for ORDI create more frequent settlement opportunities compared to traditional 8-hour cycles. The Cosmos appchain architecture also reduces gas costs for funding settlements, making smaller arbitrage positions more economically viable than on Ethereum-based alternatives."},{"question":"How does Bitcoin ordinal activity affect ORDI perpetual funding rates?","answer":"High Bitcoin ordinal inscription activity typically drives ORDI spot prices up faster than perpetual contracts can adjust, creating positive funding rates as longs pay shorts. Network congestion and high Bitcoin fees often correlate with increased ORDI volatility and funding rate extremes on dYdX."},{"question":"What's the minimum position size for effective ORDI funding rate arbitrage on dYdX?","answer":"Given dYdX's 0.02% maker fees and typical ORDI funding rate volatility, positions should be at least $10,000 to cover transaction costs and achieve meaningful returns. The 1-hour funding intervals require more active position management compared to 8-hour cycles on other platforms."},{"question":"Are there any special risks trading ORDI perpetuals on a decentralized exchange?","answer":"ORDI's limited liquidity on DEXes means larger positions face significant slippage risks during volatile periods. The token's correlation with Bitcoin network activity can create unexpected funding rate spikes when ordinal inscription demand changes rapidly, requiring careful risk management."}]}]
